d large file size. I see the prompt requests details (scenery with descriptions), but the strict `responseSchema` of `gemini-2.5-flash` may be preventing that. If the model *is* trying to include \'details\' when the schema doesn\'t support it, this could cause issues. Conversely, I checked `monsterSchema`, which is included as part of `roomSchema`, which does seem correct.\n\n\n**Examining Line Length**\n\nI\'m now investigating potential causes for extremely long lines in the JSON response, specifically focusing on the `description` fields or possible model hallucinations. While making the parsing more robust is an option, it won\'t fix an unterminated string. The core problem appears to be excessive response length; 3-5 rooms shouldn\'t result in a 334KB file size. I am also checking `aiService.ts` for possible causes. I am going back to re-examine the `worldSchema`.\n\n\n**Adapting Schema Structure**\n\nI\'m now changing my strategy: if I intend the AI to provide \'details\', and `responseSchema` is active, then I *must* include it within the schema. Since dynamic keys are problematic with the current schema constraints, I should use an array of objects to represent those \"details\", with properties for `keyword` and `description`. This change will prevent a schema mismatch. But I will keep looking at the excessive response length.\n\n\n\n**Implementing JSON Repair**\n\nI\'m now focusing on directly addressing the unterminated JSON string. To gain more visibility, I\'ll log the `jsonText` length and add a snippet to the UI if parsing fails. I\'ll also implement a basic \"repair\" function, using a try-catch block around the JSON parsing to catch the error. If successful, I\'ll check the schema for `details`, and if it\'s there, I\'ll properly define it so the AI doesn\'t get confused. If not, I\'ll remove the prompt.\n\n\n**Constraining Object Generation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a possible root cause for the massive JSON size. I\'ve realized that the AI might be generating too many items/monsters due to the schema and prompt structure. Specifically, I\'m checking if the array-based schemas, such as `loot` within `monsterSchema` and `items` within `roomSchema`, have a potential for causing the model to get \"stuck\" by generating massive arrays of items. I\'m adding limits to the prompt regarding number of items and monsters.\n\n\n**Refining Parse Attempt**\n\nI\'m now implementing JSON \"repair\" and improved parsing. I will use a try-catch block and implement a function to handle potential markdown wrappers. Specifically, I\'m aiming to clean up markdown code block wrappings. I\'m also limiting the number of rooms and items in the prompts, and double checking the model is, as specified, `gemini-2.5-flash`. I am also adding a check on the `details` schema.\n\n\n**Implementing String Repair**\n\nI\'m now implementing a basic JSON repair function to address the unterminated string issue, adding braces and brackets where they seem missing, plus handling escaped characters and in-string conditions. This will be integrated into the parsing process, to provide more resilient handling of JSON responses. I am also planning to apply this repair before parsing.\n\n\n**Limiting Narration Detail**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the large response size and unterminated string. I suspect the `startingNarration` field within `worldSchema` might be excessively long. I\'ll add a `maxLength` constraint to the prompt. Given the specified model restrictions, I\'m checking the current model being used: `gemini`.\n\n\n**Verifying Model Usage**\n\nI\'m now going to confirm the model configuration. The task is complex text, so I should be using `gemini-3.1-pro-preview`. I\'ll cross-reference the `package.json` to verify the user\'s available models. I need to make sure I am using the best model for complex text tasks. I will need to check what is in `package.json`.\n\n\\n\\n\nI\'m now implementing the correct model, `gemini-3.1-pro-preview`, for this 