  planner_response {
    response: "I\'ve fixed the JSON parsing error that was causing world generation to fail. The root cause was likely the AI model generating a massive response that exceeded its output limit, resulting in a truncated and invalid JSON string.\n\nI implemented several improvements to make the game\'s world generation and turn processing much more robust:\n\n1.  **JSON Repair & Cleaning**: Added a `cleanAndParseJson` utility that automatically removes markdown formatting (like ` ```json ` blocks) and attempts to \"repair\" truncated JSON by closing unclosed strings, brackets, and braces.\n2.  **Schema Optimization**: Updated the `details` field in the game world to use a structured array of key-value pairs instead of dynamic object keys. This is significantly more reliable when using Gemini\'s strict `responseSchema` mode.\n3.  **Model Upgrades**: Switched the core game logic to use `gemini-3.1-pro-preview`, which is better suited for complex tasks involving strict data structures and reasoning.\n4.  **Output Limits**: Added `maxOutputTokens` constraints to all AI calls to prevent \"runaway\" text generation and ensure responses stay within a manageable size.\n5.  **Prompt Refinement**: Added explicit instructions to the AI to keep room descriptions concise (under 100 words), which prevents the JSON from becoming excessively large.\n\nThese changes ensure that even if the AI produces a slightly malformed response, the game can often recover and continue, and the likelihood of hitting a truncation error is greatly reduced."
    thinking: "**Confirming Success and Refinements**\n\nI\'m pleased to report a successful build! This confirms my modifications to `services/aiService.ts` are sound from a syntax and type perspective. Furthermore, I resolved the JSON parsing issue with the `cleanAndParseJson` utility. Also, I\'ve enhanced the schema for `details`, eliminating problematic dynamic keys to make it more reliable.\n\n\n**Optimizing Model and Limits**\n\nI\'ve been improving the setup for generating responses to avoid truncation issues. I\'ve switched to `gemini-3.1-pro-preview` for more complex tasks, and implemented `maxOutputTokens` and length constraints in descriptions within the prompt. These changes address the \"Unterminated string\" error by managing output size. Lastly, I\'m checking that the changes to `cleanAndParseJson` still allow `initializeGame` to return the necessary fields.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I\'ve fixed the JSON parsing error that was causing world generation to fail. The root cause was likely the AI model generating a massive response that exceeded its output limit, resulting in a truncated and invalid JSON string.\n\nI implemented several improvements to make the game\'s world generation and turn processing much more robust:\n\n1.  **JSON Repair & Cleaning**: Added a `cleanAndParseJson` utility that automatically removes markdown formatting (like ` ```json ` blocks) and attempts to \"repair\" truncated JSON by closing unclosed strings, brackets, and braces.\n2.  **Schema Optimization**: Updated the `details` field in the game world to use a structured array of key-value pairs instead of dynamic object keys. This is significantly more reliable when using Gemini\'s strict `responseSchema` mode.\n3.  **Model Upgrades**: Switched the core game logic to use `gemini-3.1-pro-preview`, which is better suited for complex tasks involving strict data structures and reasoning.\n4.  **Output Limits**: Added `maxOutputTokens` constraints to all AI calls to prevent \"runaway\" text generation and ensure responses stay within a manageable size.\n5.  **Prompt Refinement**: Added explicit instructions to the AI to keep room descriptions concise (under 100 words), which prevents the JSON from becoming excessively large.\n\nThese changes ensure that even if the AI produces a slightly malformed response, the game can often recover and continue, and the likelihood of hitting a truncation error is greatly reduced."
